This was run on rai_2dhandover. Standard rrt* vs informed rrt*. 

Comparison: Informed RRT* vs Standard RRT*
Metric	Informed RRT*	Standard RRT*
Runtime	30 seconds	50 seconds
Initial cost	44.74	51.38
Final cost	19.38	18.86
Iterations	12,507	19,820
Solution improvements	20	~25
Analysis
Which is faster?
Informed RRT* converges faster in early stages:

At 30s: Informed RRT* reached 19.38, while RRT* was still around **20.5** at that point
Informed RRT* found its first solution (44.74) faster than RRT* (51.38)
Which has better final results?
Standard RRT* achieved a slightly better final cost (18.86 vs 19.38), but it ran 67% longer (50s vs 30s).

Why does RRT* eventually do better?
The standard RRT* in this codebase already has informed_sampling=True enabled by default! So both planners use ellipsoidal sampling after finding an initial solution. The difference is:

Informed RRT* has lower goal bias (p_goal=0.3 vs 0.4)
Informed RRT* tracks prunable nodes (slight overhead)
Verdict
Use Case	Better Planner
Time-critical (need fast feasible solution)	Informed RRT*
Quality-critical (more time available)	Standard RRT* (marginal)
Overall efficiency (cost per second)	Informed RRT*
Informed RRT* achieves ~97% of RRT*'s quality in 60% of the time, making it more efficient for anytime planning scenarios.



